    "title": "Understanding heart palpitations and menopause",
    "content": "Although menopause is a natural transition, it can come with some uncomfortable side effects. Common symptoms include vaginal dryness, difficulty sleeping, low mood, anxiety, reduced sex drive, and problems with memory and concentration.\nHeart palpitations are not widely talked about in relation to menopause and are thus more likely to take menopausal people by surprise. They can occur due to hormone changes during menopause, and they are often temporary.\nHeart palpitations are heartbeats that are suddenly more noticeable than regular heartbeats. They may occur due to a rapid heart rhythm, such as from an arrhythmia or extra beats.\nDuring a palpitation, the heart may pound, flutter, race, or beat irregularly. Palpitations can vary in duration, lasting seconds, minutes, or longer.\nPalpitations may seem alarming, but they are often harmless and do not necessarily signal a serious problem. However, it is a good idea to speak with a doctor if they occur to ensure there is no concerning underlying cause.\nSomeone who sometimes feels their heart racing or missing a beat could be experiencing palpitations as part of menopause .\nAccording to a 2021 review based on limited publications about palpitations in menopause, up to 40.2% of perimenopausal people and 54.1% of postmenopausal people experience palpitations.\nPerimenopause is the time before menopause. Menopause occurs when someone who menstruates has not had a period for 12 months. Afterward, these people are in the postmenopausal phase.\nSome people may experience changes in heart rate in line with menopause symptoms. For example, the Endocrine Society suggests a person’s heart rate can rise 8 to 16 beats per minute during a hot flash.\nHeart palpitations during menopause may be a direct result of lower levels of the hormone estrogen . However, more research is necessary to understand exactly why palpitations may affect menopausal people.\nIf someone experiences heart palpitations during menopause, a doctor may ask them to keep a symptom journal to observe whether the palpitations occur alongside any other symptoms or triggers.\nIt is important to note that current research into heart palpitations and menopause is limited. More studies are necessary to understand a link between the two.\nPalpitations are a symptom that can have various underlying causes, including :\nAlthough they can occur as a natural bodily response, some types of palpitations, such as atrial fibrillation and ventricular tachycardia, can be serious and require treatment.\nIt is important to speak with a healthcare professional if someone experiences changes in their heartbeat. A doctor can carry out a diagnosis to understand the likely cause and provide suitable treatment, which may include medication to prevent complications.",
    "summary": "Although menopause is a natural transition, it can come with some uncomfortable side effects. Common symptoms include vaginal dryness, difficulty sleeping, low mood, anxiety, reduced sex drive, and problems with memory and concentration.",
