    "title": "BMI for females: How to calcuate, possible benefits and drawbacks, and other methods",
    "content": "BMI is an estimate of body composition based on weight and height. For people of any sex, a moderate BMI is usually 18.5 to 24.9. For people assigned female at birth, BMI does have some limitations.\nBody mass index (BMI) measurements can help someone understand whether they have a moderate weight.\nPeople who know their weight and height can use a calculator to work out their BMI.\nIn this article, we provide a BMI calculator, discuss the pros and cons of BMI measurements, and explain some other methods that people assigned female at birth may find useful for keeping track of their health.\nA person can use this calculator to figure out their BMI:\nThe BMI scale is the same for people of all sexes. The ranges for BMI from the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute are as follows:\nBMI can help people understand if their weight is moderate for their height. Knowing this may help people take steps to manage their weight if necessary, or to maintain their current weight if it falls in the typical range.\nAs a measurement, BMI is also easy and inexpensive to measure.\nWhile BMI often correlates with body fat levels, it does not accurately measure body composition. As a result, it can be a misleading measurement of a person’s overall health.\nThis is particularly true for people who are very muscular, peri- or postmenopausal , or have abdominal fat but are otherwise a moderate weight.\nMuscle tissue is denser than fat tissue. This means that people with high levels of muscle may have a high body weight that classifies them as having overweight or obesity according to the BMI scale, even if they have a low body fat percentage.\nPeople with high levels of muscle mass and a high BMI typically have a lower risk of death than those with a high BMI score and lower muscle mass.\nA high body fat percentage may harm health even if a person has a typical BMI. People with a moderate BMI but a high percentage of body fat may have a higher risk of developing metabolic syndrome.\nMetabolic syndrome is a collection of risk factors that increase the risk of heart disease and type 2 diabetes . These risk factors include high blood pressure , abdominal obesity and high fasting glucose levels .\nAdditionally, the body’s proportion of muscle, fat, and bone typically changes as people age. The average woman loses roughly 13 pounds of muscle and bone between the ages of 25 and 65, while belly fat increases to four times its previous amount.",
