    "title": "Repatha and pregnancy, breastfeeding, and birth control",
    "content": "It’s not known whether Repatha (evolocumab) is safe to receive while pregnant or breastfeeding. Certain factors may determine whether you can receive the drug during this time.\nIf you may be or can become pregnant, it’s important to consider whether Repatha is a safe option for you.\nIt isn’t known whether you can receive Repatha during pregnancy. There’s not enough information from the drug’s clinical trials or other studies about the use of Repatha in pregnant people. If you’re planning a pregnancy or can become pregnant, talk with your doctor before receiving this medication.\nDoctors prescribe Repatha to treat high cholesterol and reduce the risk of serious health problems in people with heart disease. It’s important to note that not treating your diagnosed condition during pregnancy may also carry certain risks.\nBecause of this, you and your doctor should discuss the risks and benefits of receiving Repatha while pregnant versus not treating your condition during pregnancy.\nIf you do become pregnant while receiving Repatha, the drug manufacturer (Amgen) encourages you and your doctor to notify their pregnancy safety study. This study is a collection of data from people who have taken certain medications while pregnant. The data helps determine whether the medication may be safe to take during pregnancy. You can learn more by calling 800-772-6436 or visiting the study website .\nIf you’re currently breastfeeding or planning to do so, it’s important to understand the effects that Repatha could have on you or the breastfed child.\nIt’s not known whether Repatha is safe to receive while breastfeeding. Scientists don’t know whether the drug passes into breast milk or what effect it could have on a breastfed child. In addition, no clinical trials of Repatha and breastfeeding in people or animals are available. If you’re currently breastfeeding or planning to breastfeed, talk with your doctor about the risks and benefits of receiving Repatha.\nIf you’re sexually active and you or your partner can become pregnant, it’s important to consider how Repatha could affect your birth control options.\nAs mentioned above, it isn’t known whether Repatha is safe to receive during pregnancy. If you’re sexually active and you or your partner can become pregnant, talk with your doctor about your birth control needs while you’re receiving Repatha.\nDisclaimer: Medical News Today has made every effort to make certain that all information is factually correct, comprehensive, and up to date. However, this article should not be used as a substitute for the knowledge and expertise of a licensed healthcare professional. You should always consult your doctor or another healthcare professional before taking any medication. The drug information contained herein is subject to change and is not intended to cover all possible uses, directions, precautions, warnings, drug interactions, allergic reactions, or adverse effects. The absence of warnings or other information for a given drug does not indicate that the drug or drug combination is safe, effective, or appropriate for all patients or all specific uses.",
